Description: Sit up straight. Hold a dumbbell in both hands and raise it over your head with both hands. Exhale, slowly lower the dumbbells as deeply as possible. So that both arms are bent, pressing the biceps close. Inhale, slowly lift the weight up slowly. Return to original position.

Hold a dumbbell in your left hand and kneel on the chair with your right leg. Right hand rests on the chair to create support. Hold the dumbbell in your left hand so that your biceps are pressed close to your body, your forearms are perpendicular to your body. Eyes look straight ahead.
Exhale, lift the weight, swing the weight back so that your arms are parallel to your body. The biceps remain stable and do not lock the elbow joint.
Inhale and hold your hands still for 1 beat. Return the dumbbells and arms to the starting position.

Stand straight, holding 2 horizontal bars with both hands. The legs are slightly closed in a V shape. Bend your thighs until your knees bend about 90 degrees. Tighten your  chest and shoulder muscles, use force from your arms to swing your body up so that your arms are almost completely straight
Slowly lower your body until your elbows bend at an angle of about 90 degrees, then stop.

Put your hands on the back of the chair, with your hands shoulder-width apart. Exhale, lower your body but don't let your butt touch the ground. Keep your forearms steady, your biceps will now be parallel to the floor then stop. Inhale, push yourself up slowly.

You lie on the exercise chair. Both feet are placed on the floor. Grab the barbell with both hands, the distance between your hands is slightly wider than your shoulders. Place dumbbells on your  chest. Exhale, tighten your  chest muscles, push the dumbbells up so that your arms are straight but don't lock your elbow joints. Inhale, slowly lower the barbell, expand your biceps until the barbell is close to your  chest, then stop.

Lie on the exercise bench, both feet on the floor, both hands holding the bar placed on the weapon. Exhale, exhale, push the weight up until your arms are straight. Get in, lower the dumbbells to near the deadlift, then stop, hold the position for about 1 - 2 seconds and repeat the activity.

You lie on the exercise bench. Place both feet on the floor. Each hand holds a dumbbell. Raise both arms straight up high, arms parallel to each other and perpendicular to the body. Fold your arms behind your head, exhale, move only your arms and keep your biceps steady. When the weight passes behind your head, inhale and push the weight up to the starting position.

Sit on the exercise machine, hold the handles on both sides, place your feet on the floor, and lean forward slightly. Use force from your biceps to push the handle down until your arms are straight. Stop for about 1 second at the lowest hand position, then slowly return the handle to the original position. Continue repeating the movement.

Fasten a rope handle in the lower position of a cable pulley. Stand with your back against the pulley, with a slight forward lean, and hold the rope behind your head and your upper arms next to your ears.
Straighten your elbows until your arms are fully extended.
Reverse the motion by bending your arms again.

Inhale as you lift the weight and keep it straight above your  chest. Make sure your elbows are close to your body to focus the push on your triceps. Slowly lower the weight until it almost touches the center of your  chest, but don't let it reach your  chest. This is the lowest position of the movement. Stop for 1 second at the lowest position to give your  chest muscles time to develop and bear the load.

The practitioner is in a standing position, legs spread out to the sides with a shoulder-width distance. Holding a single dumbbell, stretch your arms to hold the dumbbell in an elevated position. Slowly bend your elbows to lower the weight below and behind your head, trying to bring your forearms as close to your biceps as possible. Note, during this process only the forearm moves. You can place your other hand comfortably along the side or you can lean against the side. Slowly bring the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Facing the adjustable cable machine, grasp the rope from a high position by holding your thumbs up. Bring your elbows out to the sides so your forearms are parallel to the floor. Straighten your forearms down while twisting the rope inward so that your knuckles point toward the floor when your arms are fully extended. Pause, then return to starting position.
Stretch your arms down. Return until the forearm is close to the upper arm. Repeat. Continue with the opposite arm.

Stand straight, feet shoulder-width apart, hold the barbell in both hands, palms facing forward, place the barbell in front of your thighs and slightly bend your knees. Exhale and cross your arms across your  chest, being careful to only move your arms. Inhale and slowly relax back to the starting position..
Grasp the bar and pull it up, slowly feeling your breath

Stand straight with dumbbells in both hands, feet shoulder-width apart, then slowly push your hips back and bend forward until your body is almost parallel to the floor. Do not bend down, keep the dumbbells perpendicular to the floor. Exhale, slowly pull the weight closer to your body, to the highest position, hold for 1 second. Inhale and slowly lower the weights to the starting position.

Stand straight and hold the ends of the rope with both hands, palms facing each other. Straighten your arms and bring them close to your body. Use your biceps to pull your arms up until your biceps touch your arms, hold a shoe in this position and remember to exhale. Inhale and slowly extend your arms back to the starting position.

2 Hold a dumbbell in your hands, arms close to your body, palms facing each other. Exhale and roll up one or both arms at the same time, rotating your hands so the back of your hands faces forward. When the dumbbell is at shoulder level, stop at one rope. Inhale and slowly return to the starting position.

Sit on a flat bench, right hand holding dumbbell between legs, elbow close to right thigh, legs wider than shoulder width, left hand placed on left thigh, slightly tilted. to the right and your palm facing left. Move the right arm up horizontally and look at the right bicep. Curl the dumbbells up to shoulder height, then pause for 1 second. expiratory. Inhale and return to the starting position. Repeat a certain number of times, then switch sides.

Sit on a bench with dumbbells in both hands and elbows on the reclined part of the chair. Palms facing forward. Inhale and slowly lower your arms until you fully extend and tense your biceps. Hold your hand for 1 second. Exhale and curl your arms to the starting position, hold for 1 second and repeat.

Hold the barbell in your hands, stand straight, feet shoulder-width apart. Elbows close to the body. Exhale and pull the bar straight up. Inhale and lower the bar to the starting position. You can completely replace it with dumbbells.

Lie on a flat bench, holding the tractor with both hands, arms outstretched, palms facing you. Exhale and rotate your arms until they are close to your face, then pause for 1 second. Note that only the arms are moved. Inhale and slowly return to the starting position.

Stand up straight while holding an EZ curl bar at the wide outer handle. The palms of your hands should be facing forward and slightly tilted inward due to the shape of the bar. Keep your elbows close to your torso. This will be your starting position. Now, while keeping your upper arms stationary, exhale and curl the weights forward while contracting the biceps. Focus on only moving your forearms. Continue to raise the weight until your biceps are fully contracted and the bar is at shoulder level. Hold the top contracted position for a moment and squeeze the biceps. Then inhale and slowly lower the bar back to the starting position. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

Start out by setting the bar on the part of the preacher bench that you would normally sit on. Make sure to align the barbell properly so that it is balanced and will not fall off. Move to the front side of the preacher bench (the part where the arms usually lay) and position yourself to lay at a 45 degree slant with your torso and stomach pressed against the front side of the preacher bench. Make sure that your feet (especially the toes) are well positioned on the floor and place your upper arms on top of the pad located on the inside part of the preacher bench. Use your arms to grab the barbell with a supinated grip (palms facing up) at about shoulder width apart or slightly closer from each other. Slowly begin to lift the barbell upwards and exhale. Hold the contracted position for a second as you squeeze the biceps. Slowly begin to bring the barbell back to the starting position as your breathe in. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.

Start in a standing position with your legs shoulder-width apart. Hold a dumbbell in each hand and turn your palms toward your body. Slowly exhale while lifting the dumbbells to shoulder height. Be careful not to change your body position, just move your arms. Inhale and lower the weight slowly to return to the starting position.

You need to prepare for yourself 2 dumbbells with the most suitable weight for you. Start in a standing position with your feet shoulder-width apart and each hand holding a Dumbbell of equal weight. Place your arms along your body, palms facing inward, and this is the starting position of the Hammer Curl exercise. Keep your elbows tight, upper biceps fixed and stand straight on the floor. Move your hands and forearms, slowly roll the dumbbells forward and exhale. Continue to raise the dumbbells to shoulder height, so that your biceps are as tight as possible. Note, you can practice both hands at the same time or practice one hand at a time. Hold the weight in the top position for a few seconds, then slowly lower the weight to the starting position and inhale at the same time.

The practitioner is in a standing position, with legs shoulder-width apart. Hold a dumbbell in both hands with palms facing each other, letting the dumbbells face down toward the floor. Bend both elbows to lift the weight toward your  chest, keeping your elbows close to your body. Lower the weights in a controlled manner, straightening your elbows. Perform the movement 10 - 12 times.
Performed by lowering the body as if sitting. Strengthens quads, glutes, and hamstrings. Keep  chest up and knees aligned with toes.
Elevates one leg on a bench and performs a squat. Focuses on quads and glutes, improving single-leg stability.
Involves a hip-hinge movement. Focuses on hamstrings and glutes. Keep your back flat and knees slightly bent.
Step onto an elevated platform with one leg, engaging quads and glutes. Maintain balance and control on each step.

Performed with shoulders on a bench, pushing hips up with a barbell on the pelvis. Strengthens glutes.

Kick one leg back while on all fours. Focuses on glute activation and improves hip mobility.
Perform a squat followed by an explosive jump. Builds power in quads and calves while burning calories.

Squat with one leg while keeping the other extended. Builds strength and balance in quads.
Step sideways into a lunge position. Works inner thighs and glutes while improving hip flexibility.

Jump explosively onto a box. Works calves, quads, and glutes while enhancing power.
Step backward into a lunge. Strengthens quads, hamstrings, and glutes.
Use a machine to curl legs. Targets hamstrings. Keep movement controlled for maximum effect.

Attach a cable to your ankle and kick backward. Focuses on glutes.

Hold the barbell in front of your shoulders while squatting. Focuses on quads and core stability.
A compound movement where the barbell is placed on your upper back. Primarily targets glutes, quads, and hamstrings.
Swing a kettlebell between your legs and up to shoulder height. Activates glutes, hamstrings, and core.
Hold a dumbbell or kettlebell at  chest level while squatting. Focuses on quads, glutes, and core control.
Perform squats with a resistance band around your thighs. Activates glutes and increases resistance.
Run or walk up stairs repeatedly to improve cardiovascular fitness and build leg strength.
Straighten your legs against resistance on a machine. Focuses solely on quads.

Push legs apart against resistance on a machine. Focuses on the outer glutes.
Jumping while spreading arms and legs. It targets the legs, abs, forearms, and shoulders.
Lowering and pushing up the body using the arms. It strengthens the legs, abs, triceps, and shoulders.
Jumping while extending the arms and legs in an "X" shape. It focuses on the legs, abs, forearms, and shoulders.
Running in place, bringing heels to glutes. It targets the legs and abs.

Full-body movement involving squatting, jumping, and push-ups. It targets the legs, abs, triceps, and shoulders.
Bending at the waist and walking hands into a plank. It focuses on the legs, abs, forearms, and shoulders.
Holding the body straight in a plank position. It targets the legs, abs, forearms, and shoulders.
Running in place with knees lifted high. It works the legs and abs.

Kicking legs up and down while lying on your back. It works the legs and abs.
Seated, bringing legs in and out. It targets the abs.
A combination of crunches and flutter kicks. It works the legs and abs.
Various movements using a resistance band. It targets the legs, abs, and back.
Jumping forward from a squat position. It focuses on the legs and abs.
Side-to-side shuffling. It works the legs.
Jumping laterally from one foot to the other. It targets the legs and glutes.
Jumping with knees tucked into the  chest. It targets the legs and abs.
Lifting the upper body and legs simultaneously into a "V" shape. It works the legs and abs.
Jumping into a lunge position and switching legs. It targets the legs.

Jumping legs apart and together while holding a plank. It works the legs
Holding a plank on one side. It works the abs and forearms.
Lifting the hips while lying on your back. It targets the glutes and back.
Sitting down and twisting the torso side to side. It focuses on the abs.
Squatting and pulsing up and down. It targets the legs and glutes.
A fast movement dropping into a plank from standing. It focuses on the legs, abs, forearms, shoulders, and back.
Lifting legs from the floor while lying on your back. It works the legs and abs.
Alternating opposite arm and leg lifts. It targets the abs and back.
Alternating legs in a fluttering motion. It works the legs and abs.
Squatting with arms extended overhead. It targets the legs, abs, forearms, shoulders, and back.
Alternating lunges with jumps. It targets the legs and abs.
Jumping laterally from side to side. It works the legs and glutes.
Transitioning between forearm and full plank. It targets the abs and forearms.
Walking while holding heavy weights. It focuses on the abs, forearms, and back.
Lifting legs and touching toes with hands. It works the legs and abs.
Holding a plank with arms and legs spread wide. It targets the abs and forearms.
Jumping feet toward hands while in a plank. It focuses on the legs and abs.
Moving quickly from side to side. It targets the legs.
Lifting a dumbbell from the floor to overhead. It targets the legs, forearms, and back.

To perform this exercise, sit on a chair with your back straight and hold a dumbbell in each hand at shoulder level, with your elbows bent at 90 degrees. Exhale as you push the dumbbells upward until your arms are fully extended. Hold for a moment, then inhale and lower the dumbbells back to shoulder level. Repeat the steps for the desired number of repetitions.

To perform this exercise, sit upright on a chair and grip the barbell with your hands slightly wider than shoulder-width apart. Lift the barbell off the rack and raise it straight above your head. Slowly lower the barbell down to shoulder level. Repeat the lifting and lowering motion for the desired number of repetitions.

To perform this exercise, sit on the Smith machine, take a deep breath, and push the barbell up from the initial locked position, keeping your arms straight but without locking your elbows. Engage your shoulder muscles as you lower the barbell to chin level, pausing briefly. Then, apply force to push the barbell back to the starting position. Repeat the steps for the desired number of repetitions.

To perform this exercise, firmly grip the barbell with your palms facing down and your elbows straight. Slightly arch your  chest and pull your shoulders back while keeping your back straight and core engaged. Lift the barbell in front of you until your hands are higher than your shoulders. Hold for a moment, then slowly lower it back to the starting position. Repeat the movement for the desired number of repetitions.

To perform this exercise, stand upright with your feet shoulder-width apart. Hold a dumbbell in each hand with your arms straight down in front of your thighs. Lift the dumbbell in your right hand in front of you with your palm facing down, while your left hand remains in the starting position. Hold for a moment, then slowly lower the right dumbbell. Repeat the movement with your left hand. Alternate and repeat for the desired number of repetitions.

To perform this exercise, stand upright with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand at your sides. Lift the dumbbells up to shoulder level, holding this position for a moment. Then, lower the dumbbells back to the starting position. Repeat the movement for the desired number of repetitions.

To perform this exercise, stand upright with your feet shoulder-width apart. Hold the cable handle with one hand, while placing the other hand on your hip. Pull the cable to the side until your arm is fully extended and parallel to the floor. Hold for a moment, then lower your arm back to the starting position. Repeat the movement with the other hand, alternating for the desired number of repetitions.

To perform this exercise, stand upright with your feet hip-width apart, holding a barbell in both hands resting against your thighs, with your palms facing inward. Lift the barbell to shoulder level, keeping your elbows slightly higher than your forearms and pointing out to the sides. Lower the barbell back to the starting position and repeat the movement for the desired number of repetitions.

To perform this exercise, stand upright with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding the cable handles in both hands. Pull the weight upward until your trapezius muscles are fully contracted. Hold for a moment, then lower the weight back to the starting position. Repeat the movement for the desired number of repetitions.

To perform this exercise, stand upright with a dumbbell in each hand, arms straight down by your sides, and palms facing your body. Raise the dumbbells until they are close to your chin, bending your elbows and keeping them pointing upward. Hold for a moment, then lower the dumbbells back to the starting position. Repeat the movement for the desired number of repetitions.

To perform this exercise, stand upright and adjust the cable to face level. Engage your core and pull the cable toward your face, squeezing your shoulder blades together. Hold this position for a moment, then release the cable back to the starting position. Repeat the movement for the desired number of repetitions.

To perform this exercise, sit upright on a bench, gripping the cable handle with both hands and palms facing inward. Pull the cable towards your face, ensuring your elbows are higher than your shoulders. Hold this position for a moment, then release the cable back to the starting position. Repeat the movement for the desired number of repetitions.

To perform this exercise, stand upright with your feet shoulder-width apart, gripping the resistance band with both hands and palms facing your body. Pull the band back while keeping your elbows higher than your shoulders. Hold this position for a moment, squeezing your shoulder blades tightly. Release your arms back to the starting position and repeat the movement for the desired number of repetitions.

To perform this exercise, sit on a bench with your feet together, holding a dumbbell in each hand with your palms facing inward. Lean forward slightly, bend your elbows, and lift the dumbbells out to the sides. Lower the dumbbells back to the starting position and repeat the movement for the desired number of repetitions.

To perform this exercise, sit on the machine facing inward, gripping the handles firmly with both hands. Engage your shoulder muscles and extend your arms back. Return your arms to the starting position and repeat the movement for the desired number of repetitions.

Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand. Keep forearms perpendicular to the floor, arms close to your sides. Exhale, lower into a half squat, then stand up, pressing one arm overhead. Slowly return your arm to the starting position and repeat.

Hold the dumbbells on your thighs, feet shoulder-width apart. Use your thighs to lift the dumbbells to your shoulders, rotating your palms inward. Inhale, brace your shoulders and back, and press the weights up, rotating palms outward until the dumbbells nearly touch (without locking elbows). Exhale and hold briefly. Inhale, brace your shoulders, and slowly lower the weights, rotating palms inward back to the start.

Sit upright on a bench (use a rack if available) with the barbell above head height. Grip the bar slightly wider than shoulder-width with palms facing forward. Lift the bar overhead. Inhale, then slowly lower it to shoulder level. Exhale and press the bar back overhead, keeping your torso steady and back straight.

Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell over your left shoulder. Step forward with your right leg, lowering into a lunge until your thigh is parallel to the floor, while pressing the dumbbell overhead. Hold for 5 seconds, then return to the starting position. Repeat with the opposite leg.

Stand upright, holding a barbell with weight on one side, resting it on your shoulder. Lower into a squat, then stand up quickly while pressing the bar overhead. Hold for 1â€“2 seconds, then slowly lower it back to shoulder level.

Stand upright with feet shoulder-width apart, holding a weight plate with both hands, arms extended with a slight bend at the elbows and the plate near your hips. Exhale and gradually lift the plate until your arms are parallel to the floor, holding it for 1 second with a stable torso and straight back. Inhale and lower the plate back to the starting position.

Stand upright with feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand. Lean forward until your torso is nearly parallel to the floor, with a slight bend in your knees and arms extended in front. Exhale and engage your shoulders to raise both arms out to the side until they are parallel to the floor, keeping a slight bend in the elbows. Inhale and slowly return to the starting position.
This exercise involves hinging at the hips and rowing a weight towards your torso. It targets the middle and lower back muscles.
Using a lat pulldown machine, pull the bar down towards your  chest. This exercise targets the latissimus dorsi muscles.
Sit on a seated cable row machine and pull the handle towards your torso. This exercise targets the middle back muscles.
Using a resistance band, pull the band apart in front of you. This exercise targets the rear delts and middle back muscles.
Lie face down on the floor and lift your arms and legs simultaneously. This exercise targets the lower back muscles.
Hinge at the hips and lower your torso towards the ground. This exercise targets the hamstrings and lower back muscles.
Using a T-bar row attachment, pull the weight towards your torso. This exercise targets the upper and middle back muscles.
This exercise targets the upper back muscles.
This exercise targets the upper back muscles using dumbbells.
Lie face down on a bench, using your hands to support your upper body against the edge of a table. Pull the dumbbells toward your stomach.
Lie under a bar, grip the bar with both hands and pull your body up.
Lie face down on a hyperextension machine, raising your upper body.
In a push-up position, pull the dumbbells toward your body one at a time.
Sit on a cable machine, pull the cable toward your face.
Sit on a low row machine, pull the handles toward your stomach.
Bend forward, holding the dumbbells with both hands and extending them out to the sides.
Place one foot on a bench, use your hands to support the bench and pull the dumbbells toward your body.
Variation of the deadlift, reducing stress on the spine.
Stand upright, holding dumbbells in both hands and raising your shoulders.
Similar to a barbell shrug but using dumbbells.
Pull-ups with hands wider than shoulder-width apart.
Pull-ups with hands narrower than shoulder-width apart.

Exercise_Name: seated cable row with neutral grip
Description: Sitting on a cable machine, pull the cable toward your body with a neutral grip.
The dumbbell bench press is an upper-body exercise where you lie on a bench and press dumbbells upwards from  chest level, targeting the  chest, shoulders, and triceps.
The cable crossover is a strength training exercise that targets the  chest muscles by pulling cables across the body from both sides, focusing on developing the pectoral muscles.
The  chest Press Machine is a Gym equipment designed to strengthen the  chest, shoulders, and triceps by simulating a bench press movement while providing stability and support.

The Dumbbell Flye is a  chest exercise where you lie on a bench, holding a dumbbell in each hand, and lower your arms in a wide arc before bringing them back together, keeping a slight bend in your elbows.
Lie on a flat bench, holding a barbell above your  chest. Lower the barbell to your  chest, then press it back up. Focus on your  chest, triceps, and front delts.
Lie on a decline bench with a barbell held above your  chest. This focuses on: Lower  chest, triceps.
Lower the barbell towards your  chest, then press it back up.
Lie on a flat bench, holding a barbell above your  chest. Press the barbell straight up until your arms are fully extended. Focus on your shoulders, triceps, and upper  chest.

chest dips are a bodyweight exercise primarily targeting the  chest muscles, especially the lower  chest. To perform, grip parallel bars or a sturdy chair, lower your body until your elbows form a 90-degree angle, then push back up.

The Incline Dumbbell Press is a  chest exercise that primarily targets the upper  chest muscles. It involves lying on an incline bench and pressing a dumbbell in each hand upwards. This exercise also works the shoulders and triceps.

The Incline Barbell Bench Press is a  chest exercise that targets the upper portion of the pectoral muscles. Performed on an incline bench, this movement also engages the shoulders and triceps as you press the barbell upwards from the  chest. It's excellent for building upper  chest strength and mass.

The Decline Dumbbell Press is a  chest exercise performed on a decline bench, where you press dumbbells upward from a declined angle. It primarily targets the lower portion of the pectoral muscles ( chest) while also engaging the triceps and shoulders for support. This movement helps build  chest definition and strength in the lower  chest area.

Incline Dumbbell Flyes is a  chest exercise performed on an incline bench. You lower the dumbbells out to the sides with a slight bend in your elbows, then bring them back together. This movement targets the upper portion of the  chest (pectorals) and also engages the shoulders and stabilizing muscles. It helps build  chest width and definition.

Decline Dumbbell Flyes is an isolation exercise targeting the lower  chest. Performed on a decline bench, you hold dumbbells with a slight bend in your elbows, lowering them out to the sides in an arc motion, and then bringing them back together above your  chest. This movement stretches and contracts the lower pectoral muscles, enhancing their definition and strength

Low Cable Flyes is an isolation exercise that targets the  chest muscles, particularly the pectoralis major. Using a cable machine, you start with the cables set at a low position and pull them upward in an arc, keeping a slight bend in your elbows. This motion emphasizes the inner  chest and helps improve muscle definition and stability. It's commonly used to enhance the overall shape of the  chest.

High Cable Flyes is an exercise that targets the upper  chest and shoulders. Using a cable machine, you adjust the pulleys to a high position, grasp the handles, and pull them down and together in an arc-like motion. This movement helps isolate the pectoral muscles and enhances muscle definition while providing constant tension throughout the range of motion.

The Pec Deck Machine is a Gym equipment used to isolate and strengthen the  chest muscles, particularly the pectoralis major. To perform the exercise, sit on the machine with your back against the pad, grip the handles, and bring them together in front of your  chest. This movement effectively targets the inner  chest and helps improve muscle definition and size. It's suitable for both beginners and advanced lifters.

Incline Push-ups are a variation of standard push-ups where your hands are placed on an elevated surface, such as a bench or step. This position reduces the difficulty compared to regular push-ups and primarily targets the upper  chest (pectoralis major) and shoulders (deltoids). They also engage the core for stability. Incline push-ups are great for building strength and muscle endurance, especially for beginners or those recovering from injury.

The Decline Machine Press is a strength training exercise targeting the lower portion of the pectoral muscles. Performed on a decline bench, it involves pressing a weight (usually on a machine) away from your  chest while seated. This movement emphasizes the lower  chest and helps build overall  chest strength and muscle definition. It's a safer alternative to free weights for isolating the  chest muscles.

The Smith Machine Bench Press is a weightlifting exercise that involves lying on a bench and pressing a barbell attached to a Smith machine. This machine stabilizes the bar, allowing for a controlled movement. It primarily targets the pectoralis major ( chest muscles), while also engaging the triceps and shoulders. Th

The Smith Machine Incline Press is an exercise targeting the upper  chest, shoulders, and triceps. It involves lying on an inclined bench set at about 30 to 45 degrees and pressing a barbell attached to a Smith machine upward. The guided movement provides stability, making it easier to focus on the pressing motion and effectively isolate the upper pectoral muscles.

The Machine  chest Press is a strength training exercise performed on a specialized machine designed for  chest workouts. You sit down with your back against the support, grasp the handles, and push the weights forward until your arms are fully extended. This exercise primarily targets the pectoral muscles, while also engaging the triceps and shoulders for support. It provides stability and is ideal for beginners and those looking to isolate the  chest muscles effectively.

The Svend Press, or Plate Squeeze Press, is an exercise that targets the  chest and shoulders. To perform it, hold a weight plate with both hands, pressing it together in front of your  chest while extending your arms outward. The squeezing action engages the  chest muscles, while the pressing motion helps develop shoulder stability. It can be performed standing or seated and is effective for building upper body strength and enhancing muscle activation in the pectorals.

The Resistance Band  chest Press is an exercise that targets the  chest, shoulders, and triceps. To perform it, anchor a resistance band behind you at  chest level, hold the handles, and stand with your feet shoulder-width apart. Press the bands forward until your arms are fully extended, then return to the starting position. This exercise effectively mimics the motion of a bench press while providing variable resistance throughout the movement.

Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, knees slightly bent, holding a medicine ball (or dumbbell) in both hands. Keeping shoulders down, engage abs, bend elbows slightly and rotate torso to right until arms are in line with body

Stand with your feet shoulder width apart. Put your left hand behind your head and your right hand at your side. Bend your body to the right and lower your right hand towards the floor. Return, switch side and repeat
Rotate your arm in a small circle, then gradually increase it. Warm up your shoulder muscles and arm joints
Stand straight, swing your legs back and forth in a front-to-back or horizontal direction. Warm up your hips and leg muscles.
Raise one leg and rotate your hips to move your leg to the side as if you were stepping over a fence. Put your foot down, then switch to the other foot.
Slowly lift your shoulders toward your ears. Roll them forward in a circular motion
Raise one arm straight overhead. Bend your elbow to bring your hand behind your head, reaching down between your shoulder blades.
Shift your weight onto one leg. Bend the opposite knee and bring your heel toward your buttocks. Grasp your ankle or the top of your foot with your hand.
Slowly lower your torso forward, reaching your arms out in front of you. Rest your forehead on the mat or floor.

Lie face down on the floor with your legs extended straight back, feet hip-width apart, and tops of your feet pressing into the mat. Place your hands under your shoulders with your elbows close to your body.
Stand or sit up straight with your feet hip-width apart, shoulders relaxed, and arms at your sides. Take a deep breath in to help you prepare for the stretch.
